This was the first and last restaurant I went to before my operation for tongue cancer across the street at Columbia Presbyterian Hospital where I have a scheduled checkup today with my cancer in remission. This will be always be a special place but now trying it out again after the pandemic begins to subside it reminds one why we do this. This is quality food, with excellent service at relatively cheap prices in a beautiful dining room. This restaurant is what makes NYC great. I hope you enjoy it too.

I love the food & drinks here, but the service is really bad. I called in a take out order, and I entered the restaurant. No one greeted me. The waitresses were busy, so I let it slide at first, but they took the time out to greet every other person who came in - except for me. They seated a couple, took another individuals order and helped another person with a pickup without even acknowledging that I was there.  I stood around for 20 minutes, none of them made any effort to help me, despite me trying to flag them down. The only visible difference between me and the other patrons was that I was black, and they were not. I'm not making any accusations, but that's the simple fact of the matter. I was the only black person in the establishment, and also the only person who did not receive any service. I left without my pick up order. Won't be returning here, which sucks because I do love their food!

Ordered delivery from their last night and it was, as always a pleasure. With respect to timing I was really impressed as was 5-10 minutes before the predicted time (which is always a benefit when you consider how I always order when I’m already starving). This haste on its own is a massive benefit. Moreover the food itself was a pleasant reminder of how skilled the chefs are here. I got the Panag curry which is my general go to. With this dish they are able to make something really special by blending just the right amounts of flavor with spice you are able to get an y forgettable dish without the unpleasant experience of the spice overpowering the dish. Would definitely recommend as my go to Thai place in Washington heights.

POOR CUSTOMER SERVICE!!!! My Co-workers will be doing business elsewhere. We ordered lunch from this restaurant this afternoon through seamless. The order was missing one part. The customer friendly thing to do is call the restaurant and inform them of this issue. Upon calling and stating the order was incomplete. We were questioned several times as to whether or not we missed it in the bag. We order 6 items, received 5, how do you miss it when its clearly not present. The manager proceeded to continue to tell us how the packer stated it was in there. How she would have to pay the money back out of her pocket for the item. And if I wanted to receive what I paid for it would take longer since my location was far and the delivery person was still out delivering. That's when enough was enough and the final request was to refund the amount of the item along with the tax! I told her if I had not called you would have had my money and my food item in your possession and you would not have called me to return either one. GIVE ME MY MONEY! Seamless called from Chicago and returned my $7.62. And we made it known she had the audacity to continually not believe us. We spent almost $50 for lunch we want what we paid for simple as that. I gave it two stars cause the food wasn't bad.

As a Thai food lover, I was excited to try out a new Thai place, especially one with almost 4.5 stars on Google Maps. The restaurant was spacious and looked nice, and they had a lunch special which is always appreciated. I ordered a spring roll, and unfortunately it came out with the sweet & sour sauce already on top of the roll, which made the normally crispy outside soggy. I ordered the Thai basil fried rice, as to me that is the benchmark against which all Thai food is judged. The only positive thing I can say about the dish is that it came out hot. There was no color in the bowl, it came with one cross section of a green pepper and two small cross sections of a long hot pepper. It was very bland boring.  As a spice lover, I asked for the spice rack, and what I got was the all too familiar garlic sriracha. Needing more spice, I asked for some more peppers to put in the dish. Our waitress informed me they don't have any on hand. I asked if they could bring me some from the kitchen, and the response was unbelievable: they would have to charge me more for extra long hot peppers. Absolutely egregious. I have to pay more because I didn't have an option to choose how spicy my dish was like in most Thai places, and got two tiny pieces of hot pepper? Shocking.  In recap: lost one star for wanting to charge me more for hot peppers, lost one star for the bland food, and lost a third star for slow and inattentive service, despite an almost empty restaurant.  Don't believe the reviews, this is not a 4.5 star Thai restaurant. Another shame for the dining desert that is the Washington Heights area.

While undergoing tongue cancer radiation treatment at Columbia Presbyterian Radiology across the street I asked the staff for a restaurant recommendation, knowing my taste buds were compromised. To my delight and surprise this was the first meal that tasted, not only normal, but exquisite and inexpensive. For $14 with tip i got a delicious and huge bowl of chicken pad Thai and a spring roll. THIS is the restaurant to go to if you are either in the neighbourhood or the hospital and they deliver to the hospital. It made me feel hope, dignity and humane again to taste something this good. That is what life is about. Be grateful for your taste buds and all your senses. Bon appetit and good health to you.

The place is nice and quite and very comfortable. The decor is to my style. Very magickal if you will. The food is top notch authentic Thai. The flavors are very natural and have a nice kick of spice. I had the Chicken Satay as an appetizer and it was the bomb. For an entree I had the pineapple fried rice with a side of sweet chili Thai sauce and It couldn’t have been any better. I never seen such a combination of flavors put together so magically. It hit the spot. I also tried the Tom Kha soup which is a coconut and mushroom soup. That doesn’t sound so nice but don’t be fooled! That was one of the best soups I had in my LIFE! The food is solid. It hits the spot, tastes good, service is attentive and fast. My issue? I asked for a to go container for the rest of my Tom Yum Noodle Soup. I ate one third and then had to go. Whomever packed my leftovers THREW OUT some of it so it could fit into a much smaller container. The size of the meal, though a lunch special, is clearly an entree. It's a lot. BUT I got leftovers that added up to the amount of a very small soup. I pay for the meal and that means all of it and therefore I expect to keep all of what I pay for. This is one of those places that, though everything else seems great, will try to throw out any bit of your food without asking the customer to fit it into the smallest containers they have. In fact, they will say nothing at all. That's just shameful.  This time i had to let it pass...Next time, however, my people and I will have to pack our own leftovers.
